# Core Standards

Use these rules as the default operating contract for all changes.

## Platform Baseline

- Target **C# 15** and **.NET 11**.
- Treat preview-only language or framework features carefully. Prefer them only when the repository already opted in or the change explicitly requires them.
- Use only English in source files, docs, commit messages, PR summaries, ADRs, and generated content.

## Delivery Rules

- Make the **smallest complete change** that solves the problem.
- Keep changes **atomic**. One logical change set per commit.
- Stage only the exact files required for that commit.
- Do not combine refactors, new features, fixes, and formatting-only edits unless they are inseparable.
- When changing behavior, add or update tests in the same change.

## Repository Discipline

- Read existing code before proposing patterns.
- Prefer existing project conventions over generic examples.
- Do not introduce a new dependency unless the benefit is concrete and local alternatives are clearly worse.
- Prefer explicit code over clever code.
- Favor deterministic behavior, stable APIs, and maintainable designs.

## Quality Gate

Before considering work complete, ensure the intended workflow passes:

- `dotnet restore`
- `dotnet format --verify-no-changes`
- `dotnet build --configuration Release`
- `dotnet test --configuration Release --no-build`

If the repository has additional validation scripts, run them too.

